Stack Overflow 2017 survey analysis¶

Business stakes¶

As a company, recruiting a new member is a big investment. When the company found the perfect candidate for the position, the next challenge is to be able to keep this member in the team he belongs, even more when we are talking about tech profiles, where a lot a jobs are vacant. It might be stupid to say but, these days where the more it comes, the more people tend to be freelance, if an employee is satisfied of his job, the probability for him to quit your company is the lowest. But, what is a satisfying job?

Data given by Stack Overflow¶

In the survey made by Stack Overflow, there are 2 key questions: job and career satisfactions. In these questions, responders rate their satisfaction about their job and career. Job satisfaction will be my entry point, I will correlate these answers to the other.

The questions¶

As a senior developer, satisfied of his career and job, I would like to focus on these two points by replying to this questions:

  1. Which are the jobs that statisfied the most the repliers?
  2. In which countries are located the most?
  3. What are the main caracteristics of a satisfying job?

def get_country_continent_data(country_name):
    """
        Get country and continent data easier to use than country name itself.
        
        :param country_name: The name of the country
        :type contry_name: string
        :return: a Serie with country code on 2 alpha, on 3 alpha, continent name and continent coutry code.
        If not found, all values are set to None.
        :rtype: object
    """
    country_alpha2 = None
    country_alpha3 = None
    country_continent_code = None
    country_continent_name = None
    try:
        country_alpha2 = pycountry_convert.country_name_to_country_alpha2(country_name)
        country_alpha3 = pycountry_convert.country_name_to_country_alpha3(country_name)
        country_continent_code = pycountry_convert.country_alpha2_to_continent_code(country_alpha2)
        country_continent_name = pycountry_convert.convert_continent_code_to_continent_name(country_continent_code)
    except:
        None
    return pd.Series([country_alpha2, country_alpha3, country_continent_name, country_continent_code])

raw_df = pd.read_csv('developer_survey_2017/survey_results_public.csv')
country_meta = raw_df.Country.apply(lambda x: get_country_continent_data(x))
df = raw_df.assign(CountryCodeAlpha2 = country_meta[0], CountryCodeAlpha3 = country_meta[1], Continent = country_meta[2], ContinentCode = country_meta[3])

schema_df = pd.read_csv('developer_survey_2017/survey_results_schema.csv')

def get_column_values_counts(df, column_name, separator=None):
    """
        Get the count of the different values of a given column in the given dataframe.
        If a separator is given, the values will be splitted according to the given separator.
        
        :param df: The source dataframe
        :param column_name: The name of the column values are wanted
        :param separator: THe separator used to split values (optional)
        :type df: object
        :type column_name: string
        :type separator: string|None
        :return: The dataframe containing every values of the column in the `column_name` column and the count in a "Count" column
        :rtype: object
    """
    not_null_df = df[df[column_name].notnull()]
    values_series = not_null_df[column_name]
    if separator != None:
        values_series = values_series.str.split("; ", expand = True).stack()
    return values_series.value_counts().to_frame(name="Count").reset_index().rename(columns={'index': column_name})

Audience¶

Before diving into the numbers, let's see what the audience looks like.

Missing values has been removed, it represent a negligible part of the whole population for the geographical questions. So the missing value population is not representative of the whole population, it can be ignored. For the developer type and job satisfaction questions, 20% of the population did not replied to this question. It can a big part, but it still represent 80% of the whole responders, which can be enough for our study. It would be a nice exercise to try to guess what those replies could be, but in my case, it allows my study to rely on real data.

import plotly.graph_objects as go

figures = []
for continent in df.Continent.unique():
    if continent != None:
        continent_df = df[df.Continent == continent].notnull().drop(columns=["CountryCodeAlpha2", "CountryCodeAlpha3", "Continent", "ContinentCode"]).sum(axis=0).to_frame(name="Sum").reset_index().rename(columns={'index': 'Question'})
        figures.append(go.Bar(name=continent, x=continent_df.Question, y=continent_df.Sum))

fig_replies_questions = go.Figure(data=figures)
fig_replies_questions.update_layout(barmode='stack', title="Replies to questions", height=700,xaxis_tickangle=-45)
fig_replies_questions.show()

)

)

    row=1,col=2
)

    go.Pie(values=europe_developers_types_df.Count.tolist(), labels=europe_developers_types_df.DeveloperType.tolist(), name="Europe"),
    row=2,col=1
)

    go.Pie(values=asia_developers_types_df.Count.tolist(), labels=asia_developers_types_df.DeveloperType.tolist(), name="Asia"),

The questions¶

I will focus on job and career satisfaction. I will consider repliers as satisfied when their reply is over or 7, unsatisfied when reply is under 5.

1. Which are the jobs that statisfied the most the repliers?¶

3. What are the main caracteristics of a satisfying job?¶

In [12]:
satisfied_count_by_answer_df = pd.DataFrame(columns = ["Question", "Answer", "Count"])
unsatisfied_count_by_answer_df = pd.DataFrame(columns = ["Question", "Answer", "Count"])
for name in satisfied_df.columns:
    if name in ["Respondent", "Country", "Continent", "ContinentCodeAlpha3", "ContinentCode", "CountryCodeAlpha3", "CountryCodeAlpha2", "Race", "Gender"] or name.startswith("StackOverflow"):
        continue
        
    satis_count_series = satisfied_df[name].value_counts()
    if satis_count_series.size == 0:
        continue
        
    satis_count_series = satis_count_series[satis_count_series > (satis_count_series.sum()/satis_count_series.size)*2]
    if satis_count_series.size == 0:
        continue
    
    unsatis_count_series = unsatisfied_df[name].value_counts()
    if unsatis_count_series.size == 0:
        continue
        
    unsatis_count_series = unsatis_count_series[unsatis_count_series > (unsatis_count_series.sum()/unsatis_count_series.size)*2]

    
    satis_question_series = pd.Series([name]).repeat(satis_count_series.size)
    unsatis_question_series = pd.Series([name]).repeat(unsatis_count_series.size)
    
    satis_df = pd.DataFrame({'Question': satis_question_series.values, 'Answer': satis_count_series.index, 'Count': satis_count_series.values})
    unstatis_df = pd.DataFrame({'Question': unsatis_question_series.values, 'Answer': unsatis_count_series.index, 'Count': unsatis_count_series.values})
    
    satisfied_count_by_answer_df = satisfied_count_by_answer_df.append(satis_df, ignore_index = True)
    unsatisfied_count_by_answer_df = unsatisfied_count_by_answer_df.append(unstatis_df, ignore_index = True)

fig_satisfied = go.Figure()
fig_satisfied.update_layout(title='Count by question and answer')

fig_satisfied.add_trace(go.Scatter(x=satisfied_count_by_answer_df.Question, y=satisfied_count_by_answer_df.Count, text=satisfied_count_by_answer_df.Answer,
                                mode='markers', name='Satisfied'))
fig_satisfied.add_trace(go.Scatter(x=unsatisfied_count_by_answer_df.Question, y=unsatisfied_count_by_answer_df.Count, text=unsatisfied_count_by_answer_df.Answer,
                                mode='markers', name='Unsatisfied'))

fig_satisfied.show()
